<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="66" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,483,1524,1550]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Comments.—</emphasis>
The Oriental 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Oriental" box="[643,770,1524,1550]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Bethylidae</taxonomicName>
fauna is poorly known, with few keys to species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Terayama, M." box="[325,530,1564,1590]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" pagination="1 - 32" refId="ref2326" refString="Terayama, M. (1993) Check list of Bethylidae of the Oriental and the Southeastern part of Palaearctic regions (Insecta, Hymenoptera). Bulletin of the Toho Gakuen, 8, 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1993">Terayama (1993)</bibRefCitation>
, in a bethylid checklist of the Oriental and the southeastern part of Palaearctic regions, cataloged just 16 species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[831,938,1604,1629]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[831,938,1604,1629]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including three from 
<collectingCountry box="[1202,1266,1604,1630]" name="India" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">India</collectingCountry>
. The majority of these species were poorly described about 100 years ago, which makes them difficult to identify.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[264,1324,284,1870]" lastBlockId="4.[264,1324,284,1070]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="67" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">
<taxonomicName authority="Azevedo &amp; Waichert, 2006" authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[312,561,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[312,561,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">Apenesia sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[572,667,1724,1750]" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from others species in the genus, because the punctuation is sparse and shallow, and the propodeal disc lacks a carina. Aside from these characteristics, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[447,610,1804,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica">
<emphasis box="[447,610,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">A. sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fouts, 1930)" authorityName="Fouts" authorityYear="1930" baseAuthorityName="Fouts" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[743,1104,1804,1830]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mindanaensis">
<emphasis box="[743,938,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">A. mindanaensis</emphasis>
(Fouts, 1930)
</taxonomicName>
but it differs from it by the different coloration, that is rufous in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fouts" baseAuthorityYear="1930" box="[800,994,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mindanaensis">
<emphasis box="[800,994,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">A. mindanaensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and black in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[1152,1315,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="66" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica">
<emphasis box="[1152,1315,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="66">A. sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Kieffer, 1913)" authorityName="Kieffer" authorityYear="1913" baseAuthorityName="Kieffer" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[264,548,284,310]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minor">
<emphasis box="[264,366,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. minor</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Kieffer, J. J." box="[380,540,284,310]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" pagination="253 - 260" refId="ref2152" refString="Kieffer, J. J. (1913) Serphides des iles Philippines. Insecta, 3, 31, 253 - 260." type="journal article" year="1913">Kieffer, 1913</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
has the clypeus truncate, with a sharpened tooth in the apex, mandibles with one tooth and a pterostigma vein, whereas 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[918,1082,324,349]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica">
<emphasis box="[918,1082,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp nov. has clypeus rounded, mandibles with three teeth and absence of pterostigma vein. 
<taxonomicName box="[1079,1238,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="percurrens">
<emphasis box="[1079,1238,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. percurrens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Azevedo &amp; Waichert, 2006" authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[340,503,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[340,503,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[511,601,404,430]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
but there is not posmarginal vein.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
The sex association in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[583,691,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[583,691,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is difficult because of the strong sexual dimorphism. Presently, there is only one confirmed association between male and female of any species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[298,406,524,549]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[298,406,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Krombein, K. V." box="[423,629,524,550]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" pagination="620 - 631" refId="ref2176" refString="Krombein, K. V. (1989) Systematic notes on some Bethylidae from Botswana: Pristocerinae (Hymenoptera: Aculeata). Entomological Society of Washington. Proceedings, 91 (4), 620 - 631." type="journal article" year="1989">Krombein (1989)</bibRefCitation>
described 
<taxonomicName authority="Krombein (1989)" authorityName="Krombein" authorityYear="1989" box="[761,1177,524,550]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="forchhammeri">
<emphasis box="[761,961,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. forchhammeri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Krombein, K. V." box="[971,1177,524,550]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" pagination="620 - 631" refId="ref2176" refString="Krombein, K. V. (1989) Systematic notes on some Bethylidae from Botswana: Pristocerinae (Hymenoptera: Aculeata). Entomological Society of Washington. Proceedings, 91 (4), 620 - 631." type="journal article" year="1989">Krombein (1989)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from a pair taken in copula in a Malaise trap. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kieffer, J. J." box="[666,837,564,590]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" pagination="253 - 260" refId="ref2152" refString="Kieffer, J. J. (1913) Serphides des iles Philippines. Insecta, 3, 31, 253 - 260." type="journal article" year="1913">Kieffer (1913)</bibRefCitation>
described both sexes of 
<taxonomicName box="[1129,1315,564,589]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philippinenis">
<emphasis box="[1129,1315,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. philippinenis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the association was not justified. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[700,863,604,629]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica">
<emphasis box="[700,863,604,629]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">A. sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is described from both sexes reared on the same host.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="67" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
Females 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1874" box="[420,527,684,709]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[420,527,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Apenesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are rarely collected. The few described females are apterous and smaller than the male. Nevertheless, the females studied in this paper are unusually big. They are slightly larger than the males, other differences being the clypeus truncate in females and rounded in males, two big teeth in mandibles in females and five in males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="67" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,412,844,870]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Biology.</emphasis>
—This species was extracted from the tunnels of the coffee white stem borer, 
<taxonomicName authority="Chevrolat" authorityName="Chevrolat" authorityYear="1863" box="[264,535,884,910]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Xylotrechus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadripes">
<emphasis box="[264,413,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">X. quadripes</emphasis>
Chevrolat
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[550,684,884,910]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[695,870,884,910]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Cerambycidae</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Azevedo &amp; Waichert" authorityYear="2006" box="[888,1132,884,909]" class="Insecta" family="Bethylidae" genus="Apenesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="67" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sahyadrica">
<emphasis box="[888,1132,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Apenesia sahyadrica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is being used as an important natural enemy of this stem borer in coffee crop in 
<collectingCountry box="[1007,1071,924,950]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[264,1324,284,1070]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,488,964,990]" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">Etymogeny.—</emphasis>
The specific epithet refers to the area name in Indian classical Sanskrit where the specimens were collected, Sahyadri, a coffee growing area in Western ghats of 
<collectingCountry box="[264,328,1044,1070]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="67">India</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
